## State Placement

**Default to local state.** Prefer `useState` in the component that needs it (70%+ of cases).

**Lift state only when:**
- Shared by 2+ sibling components **OR**
- Parent needs to control child state

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong: Unnecessary state lifting
function Parent() {
  const [searchTerm, setSearchTerm] = useState(''); // Only used by SearchBar
  
  return (
    <div>
      <SearchBar value={searchTerm} onChange={setSearchTerm} />
      <OtherComponent /> {/* Doesn't need searchTerm */}
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Correct: Local state
function SearchBar() {
  const [searchTerm, setSearchTerm] = useState(''); // Kept local
  
  return <input value={searchTerm} onChange={(e) => setSearchTerm(e.target.value)} />;
}

function Parent() {
  return (
    <div>
      <SearchBar />
      <OtherComponent />
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Lift when shared by siblings
function Parent() {
  const [searchTerm, setSearchTerm] = useState(''); // Shared state
  
  return (
    <div>
      <SearchBar value={searchTerm} onChange={setSearchTerm} />
      <SearchResults query={searchTerm} /> {/* 2nd consumer */}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Server Components default:** If using React Server Components, prefer server-side data fetching over client state.

```typescript
// ✅ Server Component (preferred)
async function UserProfile({ userId }: Props) {
  const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: userId } });
  return <div>{user.name}</div>;
}

// ❌ Client Component (only if interactivity required)
'use client';
function UserProfile({ userId }: Props) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  useEffect(() => { /* fetch */ }, [userId]);
  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

