## useEffect Rules

**`useEffect` is only for side effects and subscriptions.** Zero tolerance for derived state calculations.

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong: Derived state in useEffect
function UserGreeting({ user }: Props) {
  const [greeting, setGreeting] = useState('');
  
  useEffect(() => {
    setGreeting(`Hello, ${user.name}!`); // Derived value
  }, [user.name]);
  
  return <h1>{greeting}</h1>;
}

// ✅ Correct: Derive during render
function UserGreeting({ user }: Props) {
  const greeting = `Hello, ${user.name}!`; // Direct derivation
  return <h1>{greeting}</h1>;
}

// ✅ Valid useEffect: Side effects
function ChatRoom({ roomId }: Props) {
  useEffect(() => {
    const connection = createConnection(roomId);
    connection.connect(); // Side effect: external subscription
    
    return () => connection.disconnect(); // Cleanup
  }, [roomId]);
}

// ✅ Valid useEffect: DOM manipulation
function AutofocusInput() {
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);
  
  useEffect(() => {
    inputRef.current?.focus(); // Side effect: DOM mutation
  }, []);
}
```

**Valid `useEffect` use cases:**
- Network requests (unless using React Query/SWR/Server Components)
- Setting up subscriptions (WebSocket, event listeners)
- DOM manipulation (focus, scroll, measurements)
- Synchronizing with external systems (localStorage, third-party libraries)
- Analytics tracking

**Invalid `useEffect` use cases:**
- Calculating derived values from props/state
- Transforming data for rendering
- Filtering or sorting lists
- Formatting strings

