## Props Design

**Boolean props must have clear prefixes:** `is`, `has`, `can`, `should`.

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong: Ambiguous boolean props
type ButtonProps = {
  disabled: boolean;
  loading: boolean;
  primary: boolean;
};

// ✅ Correct: Explicitly named booleans
type ButtonProps = {
  isDisabled: boolean;
  isLoading: boolean;
  isPrimary: boolean;
};
```

**Target maximum 10 props per component.** More indicates the component does too much.

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong: 15 props indicates component needs splitting
type FormProps = {
  title: string;
  subtitle: string;
  fields: Field[];
  onSubmit: () => void;
  onCancel: () => void;
  isLoading: boolean;
  errors: Errors;
  submitLabel: string;
  cancelLabel: string;
  showCancel: boolean;
  // ... 5 more props
};

// ✅ Correct: Group related props into objects
type FormProps = {
  header: {
    title: string;
    subtitle: string;
  };
  fields: Field[];
  actions: {
    onSubmit: () => void;
    onCancel?: () => void;
    submitLabel?: string;
    cancelLabel?: string;
  };
  state: {
    isLoading: boolean;
    errors: Errors;
  };
};

// ✅ Or split into smaller components
function Form({ fields, onSubmit }: FormProps) {
  return (
    <div>
      <FormHeader title="..." subtitle="..." />
      <FormFields fields={fields} />
      <FormActions onSubmit={onSubmit} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Props object patterns:**

```typescript
// ✅ Good: Rest props for HTML attributes
type ButtonProps = {
  children: ReactNode;
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
} & React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>;

function Button({ children, variant = 'primary', ...props }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button className={variant} {...props}>{children}</button>;
}

// Usage: <Button onClick={...} disabled type="submit">Click</Button>
```

