## List Keys

**Zero tolerance for array index as key.** Keys must be stable and unique.

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong: Index as key
function UserList({ users }: Props) {
  return (
    <div>
      {users.map((user, index) => (
        <UserCard key={index} user={user} /> // Breaks on reorder/filter
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Correct: Stable unique identifier
function UserList({ users }: Props) {
  return (
    <div>
      {users.map((user) => (
        <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Fallback: Composite key if no ID
function CommentList({ comments }: Props) {
  return (
    <div>
      {comments.map((comment) => (
        <Comment key={`${comment.userId}-${comment.timestamp}`} comment={comment} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

**When items have no stable ID:**

```typescript
// ✅ Generate stable IDs on data load
const [items, setItems] = useState<Item[]>([]);

useEffect(() => {
  fetchItems().then(data => {
    const itemsWithIds = data.map((item, idx) => ({
      ...item,
      _id: `${item.name}-${idx}` // Generate once
    }));
    setItems(itemsWithIds);
  });
}, []);

return items.map(item => <ItemCard key={item._id} item={item} />);
```

**Why index keys break:**
- Reordering: `key={0}` might point to different item after sort
- Filtering: Indexes change, causing wrong component reuse
- Inserting/deleting: React reuses wrong components

